[Annotator "GM Mihail Marin"]
[PlyCount "8"]
[EventDate "2020.10.16"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 {The Nimzo-Indian Defense is one of the most
flexible openings. Against all rather numerous white systems, Black has a
practically unlimited choice of variations and the character of the resulting
positions can vary within a very wide range, depending on each player's
reactions. Among Black's openings against 1.d4, I believe that only the
Gruenfeld comes close from this point of view. Even though Alekhine had played
this opening just a few days before Nimzovich did (with a few previous games
over the previous 70 years at a slightly lower level), it was the Russian
Danish grandmaster who constantly advocated it developed it over the following
decades, justifiably becoming its godfather. Nimzovich had a few structures
which he favoured most. He was very skilled in exploiting the weakness of the
double c3 and c4-pawns, and he many times took on c3 without waiting for a2-a3.
He also liked to combine the Nimzoindian ideas with those from another opening
from his repertoire, the Queen's Indian. This meant that he many times
associated the exchange on c3 with ...b7-b6 and ...Bb7, increasing Black's
control over e4. Finally, he also used to place his central pawns on d6 and e5
to restrict the enemy dark-squared bishop. Over the decades, the perception of
the essence of this opening has changed more than once. In modern times,
players with black seem concerned about reaching a draw with the help of long
forced lines, in which Black is struggling most of the time. This "policy"
usually involves the moves ...d7-d5 and ...c7-c5, which can lead to
interesting central structures, but the current fashion is to give up the
centre with the first given possibility with ...dxc4 and ...cxd4, leading to
somewhat dull play. The repertoire built in this database is close to Aaron
Nimzovich' perception. Here is a brief mapping of the material.} 4. e3 (4. Qc2
b6 {aims at controlling e4 and even starting a kingside attack with ...Ne4 and
...f7-f5.}) (4. Nf3 b6 {is closely related, but the resulting positions can be
quite different from the concrete viewpoint.}) (4. Qb3 {is one of the
sidelines where we won't be able to use one of Aaron's favourite paths.} c5 {
keeps the game hyper-modern enough, though.}) (4. g3 O-O 5. Bg2 {practically
begs for} Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 d6 {even though Black rarely gets to play ...b7-b6.}) (
{If} 4. f3 {the best way to keep the hyper-modern spirit alive is} c5 5. d5 b5)
(4. a3 Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 {does not prevent Black from staying within his favourite
schemes.} c5 6. e3 b6 7. Bd3 Bb7 8. f3 Nc6) ({Finally,} 4. Bg5 h6 5. Bh4 c5 6.
d5 Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 d6 8. e3 e5 {reaches a blocked position with double pawns 0on
c3.}) 4... b6 {is precisely what Alekhine and Nimzovich had played in the
aforementioned games.} *

