{[%evp 0,34,19,31,25,-16,-12,2,4,17,35,10,10,-6,2,2,2,-4,-4,-7,9,18,25,23,9,20,
-36,13,16,-5,10,17,0,-16,-18,-19,4]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 {
This move introduces the Rubinstein system. I am tempted to name it the
classical system, even though this usually refers to 4.Qc2. The reason is that
White is developing quietly and smoothly, not trying to refute Black's play,
but instead looking to obtain a small edge eventually. Since White does not
put any early pressure, Black has an enormously vast range of systems. As Tal
would say, this does not mean that he can equalise with every possible move.
On the contrary, he tends to face micro problems in all of them. Both sides
enjoy a variety of plans, and it is only in the middlegame that it becomes
clear whose strategy was more successful.} b6 {As I explained in the
introduction, I believe this system is a great fit for our approach.} 5. Nge2 {
This is White's most typical reaction. Encouraged by the fact that Black does
not attack the centre with pawns, White prepares to attack the bishop with
a2-a3 without spoiling his pawn structure.} (5. a3 {transposes to the Saemisch
attack after} Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Bb7 7. f3 c5 8. Bd3 Nc6 {- see Line 39.}) (5. Bd2 {
pursues the same goal as 4.Nge2 but is somewhat more passive.} Bb7 6. Nf3 {
The only reasonable answer.} (6. f3 {White wants to go Bd3 and Nge2, but this
is simply to slow. Now, our best reaction would be} c5 {intending ...cxd4
followed by a quick ..d7-d5.  With the bishop on d2 and the pawn on f3, White
would have a weird version of an IQP.} 7. d5 {does not really work.} exd5 8.
cxd5 Nxd5 9. Nxd5 Bxd5 10. Bxb4 Qh4+ 11. Ke2 Bc4+ {wins.}) 6... Bxc3 7. Bxc3
Ne4 {We have transposed to Line 24.}) (5. Nf3 {is the main alternative to the
last move and will be covered in Lines 10 and 11.}) 5... Ba6 {This move was
introduced by Bronstein during his match with Botvinnik.  Black immediately
attacks the vulnerable pawn on c4. White has different ways of defending it,
but Black will look to exchange the light-squared bishops after ...d7-d5 and
obtain promising play on the light squares.} 6. Ng3 {This is one of the main
continuations. White invites Black to take on c3 without spending the time on
a2-a3.} ({The rare} 6. Nf4 {is less active, as it does not prepare e3-e4.
Therefore, Black can delay his pawn counterattack in the centre:} Bxc3+ 7. bxc3
Nc6 8. Bd3 Na5 9. Qe2 d5 10. cxd5 Bxd3 11. Nxd3 exd5 $11 {Black's control over
e4 and c4 compensates for White's mobile central structure.}) (6. Qa4 {Is a
rather unambitious move. However, it is good enough to restrict our options,
too.} c5 (6... Be7 7. e4 $1 $14) 7. a3 (7. dxc5 Bxc5 {leads to a comfortable
version of the Hedgehog. Here is an original example:} 8. Nf4 O-O 9. Be2 Qc8
10. Bd2 Bd6 11. Rc1 Bb7 12. f3 Nc6 13. O-O Qb8 14. g3 {With such a weak
kingside, White cannot be better.} Rd8 15. Nb5 Be7 16. Nd3 a6 17. Nd4 b5 $5 18.
Nxc6 Bxc6 19. Qa5 bxc4 20. Rxc4 Bb5 $15 {Wicker,K (2280)-Matanovic,A (2485)
London 1983 (½-½, 45)}) 7... Bxc3+ 8. Nxc3 O-O (8... cxd4 {is prematurely
opening up the c1-g5 diagonal.} 9. exd4 O-O 10. Bg5 h6 11. Bh4 d5 12. cxd5 Bxf1
13. Kxf1 g5 14. Bg3 Nxd5 15. h4 {White was enjoying a rather obvious
initiative, Aleksandrov, A (2608)-Petrosyan, M (2607) Lichess.org 2020 (½-½,
57)}) 9. dxc5 {This is White's only chance.} (9. Be2 {allows for} cxd4 10. exd4
d5 {under favourable circumstances.}) (9. d5 {is premature.} exd5 10. cxd5 Bxf1
11. Kxf1 d6 {Black has a comfortable pseudo-Benoni structure as White will
need some time to complete his development and the square on d3 is weak.} 12.
h4 Nbd7 13. h5 h6 14. Qf4 Ne5 15. Rh3 {Romanov,O (2381)-Neverov,V (2549) St
Petersburg 1999 (0-1, 40)} Nd3 16. Qf5 Nxc1 17. Rxc1 Re8 $15) 9... bxc5 10. Be2
(10. e4 d5 $1 {Leaves White behind in development.}) 10... d5 {This is the
most consistent plan given that our bishop is on a6.  After the trade of
bishops, White will experience some problems on the light squares, the
b3-square will be especially problematic. This should more than compensate for
the powerful c1-bishop that we have no counterpart for.} 11. O-O (11. cxd5 Bxe2
12. Nxe2 Qxd5 13. O-O Nbd7 {Black plans to develop his pressure on the
queenside with ...Rfc8, ...a7-a5 and maybe ...Rab8.  Therefore White decides
to clarify the situation on the queenside.} 14. Nc3 Qb7 15. Rb1 Rfc8 16. b4
cxb4 {½-½ Szabo, L-Trifunovic, P Buenos Aires 1955 Black is at least not worse.
} 17. Rxb4 Nb6 18. Qb3 Nfd5 19. Nxd5 Qxd5 20. Qxd5 Nxd5 {Black retains some
slight initiative in the endgame.  The bishop's theoretical superiority over
the knight does not apply not only because of Black's better development, but
also because there is only one queenside pawn left alive.}) 11... Bxc4 {
I believe that this is the simplest way to achieve easy equality.} (11... Qb6 {
is more popular, but White has chances to retain some advantage.} 12. cxd5 Bxe2
13. Nxe2 exd5 {White usually goes 14.b4 with some light pressure, but even
stronger is} 14. Rd1 $5 $146 Nbd7 15. Nf4 Qb7 16. b4 $14) 12. Bxc4 dxc4 13. Rd1
Nbd7 14. Qxc4 Qe7 (14... Qc7 {, keeping the possibility of ...Qe5, is an
important alternative.} 15. b3 Rab8 16. Na4 Qb7 17. Rb1 Rfc8 {The typical
regrouping.} 18. Bd2 Ne5 19. Qe2 c4 20. Bc3 Nfd7 21. b4 Nd3 22. Nb2 N7e5 23.
Bxe5 Nxe5 24. Rbc1 a5 25. Nxc4 Qa6 {The game will soon simplify to a draw.} 26.
Rd4 axb4 27. axb4 Rxb4 28. Qd2 Nc6 29. Nd6 Rxd4 30. Qxd4 Nxd4 31. Rxc8+ Qxc8
32. Nxc8 $11) 15. e4 ({Since ...Qe5 is not available,} 15. Ne4 {[%cal Gc7e5]
comes into consideration.}) 15... Ne5 16. Qa6 c4 {Increasing the control on d3
and b3.} 17. Bf4 Qc5 (17... Nfd7 18. Rxd7 Nxd7 19. Bd6 Nc5 20. Bxe7 Nxa6 21.
Bxf8 Kxf8 22. Rc1 Rd8 $11) 18. Bxe5 Qxe5 19. Qxc4 Ng4 {Black has a very strong
initiative for the pawn.} 20. h3 (20. g3 Qh5 21. h4 g5 22. Qc5 f5 {with
excellent counterplay in a highly unclear position.}) 20... Qh2+ 21. Kf1 Ne5
22. Qd4 f5 $1 {The correct move order.} (22... Ng6 23. f3 f5 {allows} 24. Qg1
$1 {Pomar Salamanca,A-Langeweg,K Beverwijk 1967 (1-0, 42)}) 23. Ne2 Qh1+ 24.
Ng1 Ng6 {with excellent compensation for the pawn.}) (6. a3 {is the subject of
Lines 5 to 9.}) 6... Bxc3+ {The simplest way of achieving good play on light
squares.} ({Years ago, I had the provocative} 6... O-O 7. e4 Nc6 {in my
repertoire.} 8. Bd3 (8. Bg5 h6 9. h4 d6 {is not too dangerous for Black. At
some point the weakness on c4 may become an issue and Black might even take
the bishop if the time is right.}) (8. Be2 $5 $146 {deserves some attention,
though.}) 8... Nxd4 {This may work, but starting such forcing play at an early
stage is a bit against our main policy.} ({I had analysed} 8... e5 9. d5 Na5 {
If White defends c4 with Qe2, Black is in time to regroup with ...Bxc3+ and ...
Ne8-d6. But when playing this line for the first time I faced the unpleasant}
10. O-O Bxc3 11. bxc3 Bxc4 12. f4 {with dangerous initiative in Peralta-Marin,
Spain 2010.}) 9. Qa4 Ba5 10. b4 d5 $5 {The only way to justify the adventurous
opening play.} 11. bxa5 (11. exd5 exd5 12. O-O dxc4 13. Bb1 Qe7 14. bxa5 b5 15.
Qd1 Rad8 16. a3 Rfe8 17. Ra2 Qe5 18. Rd2 c5 19. h3 g6 20. Kh1 {With at least
enough compensation for the piece, Kahl, F (2406)-Seben, E (2401) ICCF email
2018 (½-½, 50)}) 11... dxc4 12. Bxc4 Bxc4 13. Qxc4 Nc2+ 14. Ke2 Nxa1 15. Bb2
Ng4 16. Rxa1 Qd6 {Black is doing reasonably well from a material point of view
and White's king will need some time to reach absolute safety.}) 7. bxc3 d5 8.
cxd5 {A rather simplistic variation.} (8. Be2 {actually wastes a tempo over
Lines 3 and 4:} Bxc4 9. Bxc4 dxc4 10. Qa4+ Qd7 11. Qxc4 Qc6 12. Qxc6+ Nxc6 13.
e4 Na5 {In Line 4 White has the bishop on a3 already.}) (8. Qf3 {is examined
in Line 2}) ({For} 8. Ba3 {see Lines 3 and 4.}) 8... Bxf1 9. Kxf1 (9. Nxf1 {
does not speed up White's development.} Qxd5 10. f3 O-O 11. Ng3 Nc6 $5 $146 {
I like the idea of occupying the square on c4 as soon as possible.} (11... Qc4
12. Qb3 Qa6 13. c4 c5 {is also fine, though.} 14. dxc5 bxc5 15. Bb2 Nbd7 16.
O-O Rab8 {1/2-1/2 (33) Gamundi Salamanca,A (2400)-Franco Ocampos,Z (2480)
Cordoba 1995}) 12. O-O Qc4 13. Qb3 Na5 $11 {followed by ...c7-c5 soon.}) 9...
Qxd5 {This structure is reminiscent of the Gruenfeld Exchange variation.
Black's control over the c4-square and the possibility of active play on the
c-file compensate for White's massive centre. The structure can arise via
several move orders in this system. The knight on g3 could only be used for
attacking purposes, but without the light-squared bishop White does not have
real chances to create dangerous threats.} 10. Qd3 O-O {The most flexible.} (
10... Nbd7 {is a bit committal, as after ...c7-c5 the knight might do better
on c6.} 11. e4 Qa5 {Gligoric,S-Portisch,L Wijk aan Zee 1975 (0-1, 57)} 12. a4
$5 {It seems that Black cannot free himself with} b5 13. Qxb5 Qxc3 14. Bb2 Qd2
15. Qe2 Qb4 16. f3 {and White may retain a small plus.}) 11. e4 Qa5 12. e5 (
12. a4 {is less effective now.} c5 13. Bg5 (13. f3 Nc6 $1 {and White may have
problems on d4 soon.}) 13... Nfd7 14. h4 h6 15. Bf4 Nc6 16. Rh3 cxd4 17. cxd4
Rfd8 {With excellent play.}) 12... Nd5 13. Ne4 f5 {The typical way of making
sure the kingside is safe.} 14. Ng5 Re8 15. Bd2 h6 16. Nf3 c5 17. g3 cxd4 18.
cxd4 Qa6 19. Ke2 Qxd3+ 20. Kxd3 Nc6 $15 {Santos,M (2247)-Leitao,R (2571) Sao
Paulo 2001 (0-1, 36) There's nothing that makes up for Black's control over
the crucial d5-square.} *

