1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 b6 5. Nge2 Ba6 6. Ng3 Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 d5 8.
Ba3 {This ambitious move is aimed at preventing Black from castling short.}
Bxc4 {It does not make much sense to keep the bishop.} (8... dxc4 9. e4 {
offers White great compensation for the pawn as known since the moment this
classical game was played.} Qd7 10. Be2 Nc6 11. Qc2 O-O-O 12. O-O h5 13. Rfd1
h4 14. Nf1 Nh5 $2 15. d5 $1 Ne5 16. dxe6 Qe8 17. Rxd8+ Qxd8 18. Bxh5 Rxh5 19.
f4 Nd3 20. exf7 c5 21. Qe2 Rh8 22. e5 Kb8 23. e6 Qf6 24. Re1 Bb5 25. Bxc5 $1
bxc5 (25... Nxc5 26. Qe5+ $1) 26. Rb1 a6 27. a4 $18 {Portisch,L-Fischer,R
Siegen 1970 (½-½, 39)}) 9. Bxc4 dxc4 10. e4 {Instead of rushing to regain
the sacrificed pawn, White is rather trying to prove his compensation with
queens on the board.} ({Delaying e3-e4 offers Black additional possibilities.} 
10. O-O Qd7 11. Rb1 $6 Nd5 $1) (10. Qa4+ {is examined in Line 4}) 10... Qd7 11.
O-O (11. Rb1 {prevents ...Qb5 but wastes a tempo, allowing Black to start his
counterplay.} c5 $5 $146 12. e5 (12. O-O O-O) (12. dxc5 Qxd1+ 13. Rxd1 Nbd7 14.
Rd4 bxc5 15. Rxc4 O-O 16. O-O Rfb8 {Black is positioned extremely well, so
White's visual activity is negated.}) 12... Nd5 13. Ne4 O-O 14. dxc5 b5 {
[%cal Gd7c6,Gb8d7] Planning ...Qc6 followed by ...Nd7.} (14... Nc6 $5 15. cxb6
