1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 b6 5. Nge2 Ba6 6. Ng3 Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 d5 8.
Ba3 Bxc4 9. Bxc4 dxc4 10. Qa4+ {White gets his pawn back while also trading
queens.} Qd7 11. Qxc4 Qc6 12. Qxc6+ {There is no choice as the pawns on c3 and
g2 are hanging.} Nxc6 {I used to have this line in my repertoire with white
three decades ago. Despite Black's good results, I felt that White's centre
should promise exactly White the better chances. The point is that Black
cannot castle short. This makes...c7-c5 unachievable While my view didn't
change much since then, I discovered that if Black actively fights for the
control over c4, his chances are not worse.} 13. c4 {The most natural move
that prevents the blockade of the c4-square.} (13. Ke2 Na5 14. Bb4 Nc4 {
is fine for Black.} 15. Kd3 (15. a4 Nd5 {Helps Black get even more active.} 16.
a5 a6 $1 {White should refrain from axb6 as this would leave Black with a
dangerous passer after ...cxb6.} 17. e4 Nf4+ 18. Kf3 g5 19. h4 Nd2+ 20. Ke3
Nc4+ 21. Kf3 Nd2+ {White should agree to a draw by perpetual.} 22. Kg4 $2 h5+
23. Kxg5 Nxg2 24. Nxh5 c5 25. dxc5 bxa5 26. Rxa5 Nxe4+ 27. Kg4 Nxf2+) 15...
Nb2+ 16. Kc2 Nc4 17. Kd3 {Black can choose between repeating moves and playing
on.} b5 18. Rhb1 Kd7 19. a4 a6 20. e4 Kc6 21. Nf1 Nd7 22. Ne3 Nxe3 23. Kxe3 Nb6
24. axb5+ axb5 $11) (13. Rc1 b5 $5 $146 (13... O-O-O {is playable with the
idea of keeping the position more complex. Objectively, White should be
somewhat better.} 14. c4 Kb7 15. Ke2 Rd7 16. f3 Rhd8 17. Bb2 Ne8 18. Ne4 h6 19.
g4 Na5 20. c5 Nc6 21. Rhd1 {Timman,J (2620)-Kortschnoj,V (2615) Dortmund 1994 
(0-1, 46)} b5 22. Rb1 a6 23. Bc3 f5 24. gxf5 exf5 25. Ng3 f4 $15) 14. c4 a6 15.
cxb5 (15. Ke2 Na5 16. cxb5 axb5 17. Rxc7 Nc4 18. Bc5 Rxa2+ 19. Ke1 Ra1+ 20. Ke2
Ra2+ {with a probable draw as} 21. Kf3 $2 {loses to} Nd2+ 22. Ke2 Nde4+) 15...
axb5 16. Rxc6 Rxa3 17. Rxc7 O-O {Due to the passive knight on g3, Black gets
his pawn back very easily.} 18. Rc2 Rfa8 19. Rb2 R8a5 20. Kd2 Rxa2 21. Rhb1 h5
22. h4 g6 $11) (13. e4 Na5 14. Ke2 Nd7 15. Rhd1 (15. Kd3 O-O-O {exposes the
king to ...Ne5.}) 15... Nc4 16. Bc1 O-O-O 17. Nf1 (17. Kd3 b5 18. a4 $2 Nc5+ $1
19. Ke2 Nxa4) 17... f5 $1 {Fighting for the light squares.} 18. exf5 (18. f3
fxe4 19. fxe4 e5 $1) 18... exf5 19. Ne3 Rhe8 20. Kf1 Nxe3+ 21. Bxe3 h6 22. a4
Nf6 23. h3 Ne4 24. c4 g5 $15 {Moreno Ruiz,J (2426)-Illescas Cordoba,M (2602)
Burgos 2003 (0-1, 57)}) 13... a6 $1 {If Black is to equalize, this move has to
be played.} (13... O-O-O 14. Ke2 Rd7 15. Rhc1 Rhd8 16. Rab1 Kb7 17. Bb2 Ne8 18.
Ne4 Nd6 19. Nd2 f5 20. Nb3 $16 {Nikolac,J (2495)-Adorjan,A (2515) Amsterdam
1978 (0-1, 41)}) 14. Ke2 b5 {The point behind the previous move.} 15. Rhc1 (15.
Rac1 {may cause some problems along the a-file.} Kd7 16. Rc2 (16. d5 Ne5 17.
dxe6+ Kxe6 $17) 16... Na5 17. c5 (17. cxb5 axb5 18. Bc5 Nc4 $17) 17... Nc4 18.
Bc1 Nd5 19. Bd2 (19. a3 f5 20. f3 Rhf8 $5 $15 {anticipating e3-e4.}) 19... f5
20. f3 a5 $17) 15... Kd7 16. d5 {The principled continuation.} (16. Nf1 {
Luminaria,I (1300)-Durand,J (1839) IECG email 2003 (½-½, 59)} Ne4 17. f3 Nd6
18. Nd2 Na5 19. cxb5 axb5 20. Bb4 Nac4 21. Nxc4 Nxc4 22. a4 {Otherwise White
would be worse.} Rhb8 23. e4 Na5 24. Bxa5 Rxa5 25. axb5 Rxa1 26. Rxa1 Rxb5 $11)
16... Ne5 17. dxe6+ Kxe6 {The most ambitious continuation that maintains the
kingside structure safe.} (17... fxe6 $5 18. cxb5 axb5 19. Bb2 Nc4 20. Bxf6
gxf6 21. a4 c6 $11) 18. cxb5 axb5 19. Bb4 Ra4 20. a3 Nc4 21. Rd1 Rc8 22. Bc5 h6
$5 {A subtle way of preparing ...Nd7.} ({In order to understand this move, we
