Re6 18. Bh3 R6e7 {[%cal Gf6e4] The threats ...Ne4 and possibly ...c6-c5 may
force a draw by repetition after} 19. Bg2 $11) 16... Bxf4 17. gxf4 Bc4 18. Na4
Ne4 19. Bc3 f5 20. Nb2 b5 21. Nxc4 bxc4 $17 {Black owns the entire board.
Manolache,M (2467)-Granda Zuniga,J (2652) Benasque 2015 (0-1, 51)}) (7. Qa4 {
[%cal Ge3e4] is rare, but requires some accuracy from Black.} Bb7 (7... O-O $6
8. e4 {Purdy, J-Deeves, K Australia 1995 (½-½, 50)}) 8. Nf4 (8. Qc2 d5 9. cxd5
Nxd5 {leaves White a bit behind in development.}) (8. Ng3 h5 $5 9. h4 $6 Ng4 {
dooms the pawn on h4.}) 8... O-O 9. Bd3 (9. b4 d5 10. c5 $2 a5 {sees White
collapse}) 9... d5 {One may argue that Black has reached a Queen's Indian
after having lost two tempi. However, White did not use this time for
constructive moves as neither his f4-knight nor his queen are optimally placed.
} 10. O-O (10. cxd5 exd5 11. b4 c6 12. O-O a5 13. b5 c5 $11) 10... dxc4 11.
Bxc4 a6 12. Qc2 Nbd7 13. e4 b5 14. Ba2 c5 $11 15. d5 e5 $5 16. Nfe2 c4 17. Ng3
Ne8 18. Nf5 Bc5 {with active play. The knight is on its way to d6.}) (7. Nf4 {
is the subject of Lines 6 to 9.}) 7... d5 8. cxd5 {This move, followed by the
next one, justify the whole idea} (8. b3 {Now, White will have a hard time
protecting his c4-pawn.} O-O 9. Be2 (9. Bd3 {prepares to defend the pawn with
Qe2 but exposes the bishop.} c5 $1 10. dxc5 dxc4 $1 11. bxc4 Nc6 $1 12. cxb6
Ne5 13. Be2 axb6 $15 {Now, Black is getting his pawn back while keeping active
play.}) (9. Bb2 c5 10. cxd5 Bxf1 11. Nxf1 Nxd5 {is at least fine for Black who
is better developed.}) (9. e4 $2 {weakens the d4-pawn and the long diagonal.}
dxe4 10. Ngxe4 Nxe4 11. Nxe4 Bb7 12. Qd3 f5 13. Nd2 Bf6 14. Bb2 c5 15. Nf3 Be4
16. Qe3 Nc6 17. O-O-O Bxf3 18. Qxe6+ Kh8 19. gxf3 Nxd4 20. Bxd4 Bxd4 $19 {
Tempone,M (2440)-Debarnot,R (2350) Buenos Aires 1990 (0-1, 26)}) 9... dxc4 10.
bxc4 Nc6 {White already has to worry about his c4-pawn.} 11. Bf3 (11. Qc2 Na5
12. Nce4 Nxe4 13. Nxe4 c5 14. dxc5 f5 15. Ng3 Rc8 $15) 11... Na5 $1 {A
promising exchange sacrifice.} 12. Bxa8 Qxa8 13. O-O Bxc4 14. Re1 c5 $15 {
Black is better developed and dominates on the light squares. With a pawn for
the exchange, he has more than enough compensation.}) 8... Bxf1 9. Nxf1 {
