1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 b6 5. Nge2 Ba6 6. a3 Be7 7. Nf4 d5 8. cxd5
{After Black's forced answer, this can lead to two different lines, which are
both rather fun.} Bxf1 9. dxe6 $5 {This dangerous piece sacrifice requires
certain accuracy from Black.} Ba6 (9... Bc4 $2 10. Qa4+) 10. exf7+ Kxf7 {
White has obvious compensation for the piece. His central pawns are rather
intimidating in the long run. A check on b3, followed by the knight invasion
on e6 may also be unpleasant. Nevertheless, practice and analysis show that
Black can maintain approximate equality.} 11. e4 {This and the next move are
the most consistent abstractly, as White refrains from early commi9tments.} (
11. Qb3+ {is also playable but has the drawback of clarifying White's
intentions a bit too early.} Ke8 12. e4 {as in Dambacher,M (2476)-Morawietz,D 
(2420) Germany 2018 (1-0, 44) is more consistent but not threatening, either.}
(12. Ne6 {continues the committing policy and allows Black to improve his
position while parrying the one-move threats.} Qd7 13. Nxg7+ (13. e4 Nc6 14. d5
{Lipiniks,L-Pachman,L Buenos Aires 1955 (0-1, 28)} Ne5 15. Nxc7+ Qxc7 16. Qa4+
b5 17. Qxa6 Rb8 $15) 13... Kd8 14. Ne6+ Kc8 15. d5 Bb7 16. Nf4 Bd6 17. e4 Re8
18. f3 Bxf4 19. Bxf4 Bxd5 $17 {Volkov,S (2628)-Vitiugov,N (2555) Tomsk 2006 
(0-1, 46)}) 12... Qd7 $146 13. e5 Nc6 $1 {This is an important idea.  If Black
had to retreat with the attacked knight, he could easily find himself crushed.
By returning the piece, though, Black will retain excellent compensation due
to his bisho' pair and better structure.  In many lines, like this one, White
would also have a hard time rescuing the king from the centre.} 14. Qa4 (14.
exf6 Bxf6 15. Be3 Nxd4 $17) 14... Na5 15. Qc2 Nc6 (15... Qxd4 16. exf6 Bxf6 17.
Be3 Qc4 18. O-O-O Bxc3 19. Qxc3 Rd8 $13) 16. exf6 Bxf6 17. Qa4 Na5 $44 {
½-½ Garau, B (2201)-Almarza Mato, C (2148) ICCF email 2013}) 11... Bc4 {
It is already vital to parry the threat Qb3+.} 12. Be3 (12. e5 Nc6 13. Be3 Re8
{may transpose to the lines discussed below.}) (12. b3 Ba6 13. b4 (13. e5 Re8
14. Nce2 $2 Nd5 $19 {The last move is possible because there we no longer need
to be afraid of Qh5+.Davis,J (2005)-Stuart,P (1989) Auckland 2011 (0-1, 62)})
13... Bc4 14. e5 Re8 15. Be3 Nc6 16. Rc1 Kg8 17. Nce2 b5 18. exf6 Bxf6 19. O-O
Qd7 20. Nh5 Bh4 21. Re1 Rad8 (21... a5 {is another way of activating the
queen's rook.}) 22. Qd2 {Goudriaan,E (2374)-Roos,A (2217) Maastricht 2013 (1-0,
74)} Ne5 {[%cal Ge5d3,Ge5g4] Threatening both ...Nd3 and ...Ng4.} 23. dxe5 Qxd2
24. Bxd2 Rxd2 {with great compensation for the pawn.}) 12... Nbd7 $1 {White's
last moves have been flexible, so Black needs to show some precision.} (12...
Nc6 $6 {misplaces the knight as the following line proves} 13. b3 Ba6 14. b4
Bc4 15. Rc1 {Gorodetzky,D (2483)-Soffer,R (2490) Jerusalem 2019 (1-0, 27).
This becomes clear after} Re8 16. Nce2 $1 b5 (16... Bxe2 $2 17. Qb3+) 17. Rxc4
$1 bxc4 18. Qc2 $16 {with some rather overwhelming compensation for the rook,
as the knight on c6 is passive and vulnerable.}) 13. e5 (13. b3 Ba6 14. b4 {
no longer works out so well} Bc4 15. Rc1 Bd6 16. Nce2 b5 17. Rxc4 bxc4 18. Qc2
Nb6 $19 {A small difference in the knight's placement with huge implications.})
(13. Qc2 $5 {[%cal Gc3d1] White is preparing Nd1} g5 $1 14. Nb5 {The most
challenging.} (14. Nfe2 Ng4 15. Nd1 Nxe3 16. Nxe3 Bxe2 17. Qxe2 Rf8 18. O-O-O
Kg8 {White has good positional compensation for the piece, but Black's
position is entirely viable.}) (14. Nce2 b5 15. Nh3 h6 {is relatively safe for
Black, too.}) 14... Bxb5 15. Qb3+ Ke8 16. Ne6 Qc8 {White can force a draw by
perpetual or continue playing.} 17. Qxb5 c6 18. Qb3 {White needs to defend the
invader knight to stop ...Nc5} (18. Qd3 Nc5 $17) (18. Qxg5 Rg8 19. Qf4 Rg4 20.
Qf3 Nc5) 18... Nxe4 19. O-O Ndf6 20. f3 Nd6 21. Bxg5 Nd5 22. Bxe7 Kxe7 23. Rae1
Kd7 24. f4 {Planning Qh3.} Qg8 25. Qh3 Qf7 26. Re5 (26. Ng5+ Qf5) 26... Kc8 {
White surely retains positional compensation for the piece, but with his
knights actively placed and the king in safety, Black has entirely normal play.
}) 13... Nxe5 $1 ({With the knight on d7,} 13... Re8 14. exf6 Bxf6 {no longer
puts pressure on d4} 15. Rc1 $5 $16) 14. dxe5 Qxd1+ 15. Nxd1 (15. Rxd1 Ng4 16.
e6+ Bxe6 17. Nxe6 Nxe3 18. fxe3 Kxe6 19. Nb5 Bd6 $11 {Wenninger,P (2296)-Ninov,
N (2445) Deizisau 2015 (½-½, 21)}) 15... Ng4 16. Rc1 Nxe5 17. Bd4 {Again,
White ends up a pawn up, but Black has a perfectly sufficient compensation due
to his bishop pair and active pieces.} Nd3+ 18. Nxd3 Bxd3 19. Rxc7 Rhc8 20.
Rxc8 Rxc8 21. Kd2 Bg6 22. Ne3 Rd8 23. Kc3 Rc8+ 24. Kb3 {The only way to avoid
a draw by repetition.} Kg8 $1 {Preparing ...Bf7.} 25. Ka2 Rf8 26. f3 Bf7+ 27.
Ka1 Rd8 28. Nf5 Bf8 29. Bc3 Rd3 $11 {Grego, L (2335)-Salewski, B (2308) ICCF
email 2014 (½-½, 39) With his king isolated on a1, White does not have
chances to convert his extra pawn. All Black needs to do is stay active in the
centre.} *

