{[%evp 0,30,25,28,28,25,21,21,29,29,15,6,26,25,22,26,51,16,24,14,25,5,7,7,-5,
-3,-5,-19,-2,-15,-25,-28,-37]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 b6 5. Nge2
Ba6 6. a3 Be7 7. Nf4 d5 8. b3 {We have seen a similar picture before. The
difference is that White does not expose his queen by means of Qf3.} O-O 9. Bb2
{The safest move order for White.} (9. Be2 {Will see White have a hard time
defending the c4-pawn} dxc4 $1 10. bxc4 (10. Bxc4 {means wasting a tempo and
helping Black strategically.} Bxc4 11. bxc4 Nc6 12. O-O Na5 13. Qd3 Qd7 {
followed by ...Qc6.}) 10... Nc6 {Going straight for the c4-pawn.} (10... Nbd7 {
is also playable:} 11. O-O e5 12. Nfd5 {Thorbergsson, F-Van den Broeck, H Munich
1958 (1-0, 25)} Nxd5 13. Nxd5 Bd6) 11. Bb2 Na5 12. Qa4 Qd7 13. Rc1 Qxa4 14.
Nxa4 c6 15. O-O Rfc8 16. Rc2 Bxc4 17. Bxc4 Nxc4 18. Rxc4 b5 $15) (9. Bd3 dxc4
10. bxc4 {keeps the possibility of protecting the c4-pawn another time with
