1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 b6 5. Bd3 {Against virtually any of
Black's continuations on the move 4, White has a choice between 5.Nge2 and 5.
Bd3. In most cases, the latter is regarded as the absolute mainline, but
against 4...b6 the former is more typical. However, the continuation examined
in this and the next line requires certain accuracy from Black, as there
cannot be anything wrong with White's policy of developing naturally. The most
popular continuation, inducing Black to develop his knight to d7. On the other
hand, White also commits his bishop.} Bb7 6. Nf3 (6. Nge2 {weakens White's
kingside and does not pose any special problems.} Bxg2 7. Rg1 Bf3 8. Rxg7 (8.
Rg3 Bxc3+ 9. bxc3 Be4 $15 {is comfortable for Black. White can regain the pawn
on g7, but the exchange of the light-squared bishops plays into Black's hands
given White has those doubled pawns on the c-file.}) (8. Qc2 Nc6 9. Rxg7 Bd6 $5
10. a3 Bxh2 {followed by ...Nh5 endangers the white rook.}) 8... Nh5 9. Rg1
Bxc3+ 10. bxc3 Qh4 11. Qc2 Nc6 {[%cal Gf7f5,Ge8c8] followed by ...f7-f5 and
---0-0-0. With the f2-pawn hanging, White will have problems evacuating the
king from the centre.}) (6. f3 {is best answered with} c5 7. a3 ({If} 7. Nge2
cxd4 8. exd4 O-O 9. O-O d5 10. cxd5 Nxd5 {White has a relatively unfavourable
Isolani version, as his pawn on f3 retsricts his activity and weakens e3.})
7... Bxc3+ 8. bxc3 Nc6 {transposing to our system against the Saemisch attack
discussed later.}) 6... Bxc3+ $5 {Entirely in the spirit of Nimzovitsch'
treatment of "his" opening. Taking on c3 without being provoked with a2-a3 is
also typical for the Huebner variation (4...c5 5.Bd3 Nc6 6.Nf3 Bxc3+). Since
the white knight has developed to f3, blocking the f-pawn, this does not mean
losing a tempo over the Samisch attack. It is worth mentioning that Black has
a relatively wide choice.} (6... Ne4 {is best answered with} 7. O-O {when
accepting the pawn sacrifice is known to be dangerous.} Bxc3 8. bxc3 O-O 9. Ne1
{allows White to start fighting for the centre without wasting a tempo on Qc2.}
) ({After} 6... O-O {Black has several possible plans.} 7. O-O ({From the
point of view of our repertoire variation,} 7. Bd2 {would be molesting,
compare to Line 23.}) {and now} 7... d5 (7... c5) (7... Re8)) 7. bxc3 d6 {
Black starts placing his central pawns on dark squares in order to restrict
the enemy bishop.} 8. O-O ({Preparing an early e3-e4 with} 8. Qc2 {typically
runs into} Bxf3 9. gxf3 c5 {when White faces certain structural problems.
Knights are perfectly suited for exploiting the enemy pawn weaknesses.} 10. Bb2
O-O 11. Rg1 Nbd7 12. O-O-O Qc7 13. h4 b5 $1 $15 14. cxb5 c4 15. Be2 Rfb8 16.
Kb1 Rxb5 $17 {Tauscher,K (2422)-Doderer,H (2467) Remote email 2014 (0-1, 57)})
8... O-O 9. Nd2 {The most natural way of preparing e3-e4.} (9. Re1 $6 {allows
Black to transpose to the aforementioned plan and leave the rook on e1
misplaced.} Ne4 $1 10. Nd2 (10. Qc2 f5 11. Nd2 Qh4 $1 {The pawn on f2 is
pinned and hanging.}) 10... f5 11. f3 Nxd2 12. Bxd2 Nd7 13. Qc2 (13. a4 a5 {
does not change anything, Fonseca, L (2031)-De Almeida, E (1945) Porto Alegre
2013 (0-1, 47)}) (13. e4 f4 {offers Black excellent attacking chances.}) 13...
Qg5 14. d5 Nc5 15. Kh1 Qh5 $15 {Ben Artzi,I (2392)-Raznikov,D (2500) Warsaw
2014 (0-1, 28)}) (9. Qe2 {allows the bishops' exchange with} Be4 $1 10. Nd2
Bxd3 11. Qxd3 c5 12. e4 Nbd7 $11) (9. Qc2 {runs into the familiar} Bxf3 10.
gxf3 c5 (10... e5 11. Kh1 c5 {is also possible.}) 11. Kh1 {White cannot
advance any of his pawns without offering Black new possibilities for his
knights.} (11. f4 Nc6 12. d5 Ne7 13. e4 Ng6 14. Qe2 Re8 15. dxe6 fxe6 $11) (11.
e4 cxd4 12. cxd4 Nc6 13. Be3 Nh5) 11... Nc6 12. Qe2 (12. f4 Rc8 13. Qe2 cxd4
14. cxd4 Nb4 15. Bb1 d5 16. a3 Nc6 17. cxd5 exd5 18. Rg1 Na5 19. Ra2 Re8 {
with a very stable position for Black.}) 12... Rc8 13. Bd2 cxd4 $5 (13... e5
$11) 14. cxd4 e5 15. Bf5 Rc7 16. Qd3 (16. Bc3 $6 exd4 17. exd4 d5 $17) {
Czerwonski,A (2392)-Markowski,T (2552) Suwalki 2017 (1-0, 62)} 16... d5 $5 {
Due to Black's better mobilisation, White faces problems keeping his
structural flexibility.} 17. cxd5 Qxd5 18. Be4 Nxe4 19. fxe4 Qd7 20. d5 Rfc8
21. f4 Nb8 (21... Na5 22. Bxa5 bxa5 23. fxe5 Qg4 {with excellent compensation
for the pawn due to the vulnerability of the white king.}) 22. fxe5 Qe8 {
White cannot keep his extra pawn and his structure is far from optimal.}) (9.
c5 {only weakens White's structure. It gets rid of the double pawns but not of
the weaknesses on c3 and c4.} dxc5 10. dxc5 Nbd7 11. cxb6 axb6 $15 {Vasilev,M 
(2442)-Pavlovic, M (2549) Cap d'Agde 2002 (0-1, 46)}) 9... c5 {The most
effective way of attacking the centre.  Abstractly, it blocks the double pawns.
Concretely, the pressure on d4 is more effective than after the main
alternative:} (9... e5 10. e4 Nc6 11. f4 $1 exd4 12. Bb2 dxc3 13. Bxc3 {
with a dangerous initiative for the pawn.}) 10. e4 (10. f4 Nc6 ({After White has
weakened e3 and e4,} 10... d5 $5 {comes into account.}) 11. Ba3 Re8 12. Qf3 d5
{Same idea as above.} 13. cxd5 exd5 14. dxc5 Na5 15. Qe2 Qc7 16. cxb6 axb6 {
with excellent compensation for the pawn, as White has lots of weaknesses.}) ({
There is no real play for White on the queenside after} 10. a4 Nc6 11. Re1 Rc8
12. Ba3 Re8 13. Qb1 h6 (13... e5 14. d5 Na5 15. e4 Ba6 {also looks fine for
Black. There is no obvious way to improve the a3-bishop and Black can prepare .
..f7-f5.}) 14. Nb3 Ba6 $11 15. e4 $6 d5 $3 16. exd5 exd5 17. Rxe8+ Qxe8 18.
dxc5 ({The point is that} 18. cxd5 {runs into} Bxd3 19. Qxd3 c4 $1 {as if} 20.
Qxc4 Na5 $19) 18... dxc4 19. Bf1 Qe5 20. cxb6 Ng4 $19 {Bruzon Batista,L (2682)
-Efimenko,Z (2703) Poikovsky 2011 (½-½, 44)}) 10... Nc6 11. d5 ({The familiar
} 11. f4 {does not work:} cxd4 12. Bb2 (12. cxd4 Nxd4 13. Bb2 e5 14. Nf3 Bxe4
15. Bxe4 Nxe4 16. Nxd4 exd4 17. Qxd4 Qf6 18. Qxf6 Nxf6 19. Rad1 Rfd8 20. Rd4
Rac8 21. Rfd1 Ne8 $17 {White has no compensation for the missing pawn, Tal, M 
(2630)-Nogueiras Santiago,J (2560) Saint John (blitz) 1988 (1-0, 44)}) 12...
dxc3 13. Bxc3 e5 $17 {This is the point. With the pawn on c7 instead of e6, as
in the similar line above, Black could not stabilize the centre.}) ({The
paradoxical} 11. Nf3 {was tried in a couple of games.} Nd7 $5 $146 {Using our
time to stabilise the centre.} (11... e5 12. d5 Ne7 13. Nh4 $5) 12. Re1 Qc7 13.
Be3 Rae8 {White cannot easily come up with a concrete plan . Depending on the
course of the game, Black could consider ...e6-e5 or ...f7-f5.}) (11. Nb3 {
is examined in Line 11}) 11... Ne5 12. Be2 (12. Bb1 Ba6 {makes White spoil his
coordination.} 13. Qa4 Qc8 14. f4 Ng6 15. Nf3 exd5 16. exd5 Re8 17. Bc2 Rb8 {
Threatening ...b6-b5.} 18. Rb1 Qg4 $5 {Trying to take advantage of White's
weaknesses and Black's better coordination.} (18... Ne4 {allows White an
interesting queen sacrifice:} 19. f5 Nxc3 20. fxg6 Nxa4 21. gxf7+ Kh8 22.
fxe8=Q+ Qxe8 23. Re1 Qd7 24. Bg5 {with initiative.}) 19. Bd1 (19. Qxa6 $2 Re2
20. Rf2 Rxf2 21. Kxf2 Nh4 22. Ne1 Re8 {with a winning attack.}) 19... Qf5 20.
Rb2 Bc8 21. Qxa7 Bd7 {White's extra pawn does not matter while Black's
initiative is becoming quite scary.}) 12... Ng6 13. f4 (13. Re1 e5 14. g3 Bc8
$11) 13... Qe7 14. Rf2 (14. Bd3 $2 {allows for a surprising trick.} exd5 15.
cxd5 Nxd5 $1 16. Nc4 (16. exd5 Qe3+ 17. Rf2 Qxd3 $19) 16... Nxc3 (16... Nf6 $19
{Georgiev,V (2555)-Frantsen,T (2122) Odense 2012 (½-½, 46)}) 17. Qe1 Nxe4 $19
{Ben Artzi,I (2408)-Hovhannisyan,R (2592) Jerusalem 2015 (0-1, 34)}) 14... exd5
15. cxd5 (15. exd5 Rae8 $17 {leaves White with serious developing problems.})
15... Nxe4 16. Nxe4 Qxe4 17. c4 Bc8 {with some compensation for the missing
pawn but not more than that.} *

