1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 b6 5. Bd3 Bb7 6. Nf3 Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 d6 8.
O-O O-O 9. Nd2 c5 10. e4 Nc6 11. Nb3 {This looks like the most logical move.
White defends the d4-pawn and leaves the path for the f-pawn clear.} a5 $1 {
This strong move is much deeper than it seems. Not only does it threaten to
undermine the d4-pawn, but also it...protects the b4-square!} ({It's worth
seeing why the b4-square matters.} 11... cxd4 12. cxd4 Nb4 13. Bb1 Bxe4 {
loses a piece to} 14. Bxe4 Nxe4 15. Qe1 $1) 12. Be3 (12. a4 $2 {allows Black
to execute the aforementioned operation under perfect circumstances:} cxd4 13.
cxd4 Nb4 {Suddenly, White has problems defending e4 and c4.} 14. d5 (14. f3 d5
$1 {leaves White vulnerable along the f1-a6 diagonal.}) 14... Ba6 $15) (12. d5
Ne5 $15 {causes the usual problems on c4.}) 12... cxd4 13. cxd4 Nb4 {The
the aforementioned idea finally works!} 14. d5 {The most consistent answer.} (14.
f3 $2 {as played in Baburin,A (2490)-Short,N (2684) Bunratty 2016 (0-1, 51)
does not consolidate the light squares at all:} d5 $1 15. cxd5 {Otherwise
White simply loses the pawn on e4.} Nxd3 16. Qxd3 exd5 17. e5 Ba6 18. Qf5 Bxf1
19. exf6 Bc4 20. fxg7 Re8 $19 {There's not even the slightest compensation for
the exchange, especially because White's knight on b3 is completely out of
play.}) (14. e5 {makes things easy for Black, too.} dxe5 15. dxe5 Nfd5 $5 {
An interesting way to make sure the kingside doesn't get weakened.} (15... Qxd3
16. Qxd3 Nxd3 17. exf6 gxf6 18. Bxb6 {is also drawish.}) 16. cxd5 Qxd5 17.
Bxh7+ {White has to make a few only moves in order to maintain equality.} Kxh7
18. Qg4 Nc2 19. Rad1 Qxe5 20. Bxb6 $11) 14... exd5 15. exd5 (15. cxd5 $2 Nxd3
16. Qxd3 Ba6 $19) {Apparently White has consolidated his space advantage but
Black did not exhaust his resources yet.} 15... b5 $1 16. cxb5 Nfxd5 {White
has two bishops and the better structure, but the activity of Black's minor pieces
keeps the position balanced.} 17. Bc1 (17. Bd4 $2 Nxd3 18. Qxd3 Nf4 $19) (17.
Re1 $5 Re8 18. Bf1 Nxe3 19. Rxe3 Rxe3 20. fxe3 a4 21. Nd4 Qg5 22. Qd2 Nd5 $11)
17... Qf6 18. Qd2 (18. Nd4 $2 Nc3 $1 (18... Qxd4 $2 19. Bxh7+) 19. Qd2 Qxd4 $1
20. Bxh7+ Kxh7 21. Qxd4 Ne2+ {wins}) 18... Rfe8 (18... Rfc8 $5 {looks more
straightforward.} 19. Be4 (19. Bb2 Qf4 20. Qxf4 Nxf4 21. Bf5 Rc4 22. f3 g6 $17
{with overwhelming activity.}) 19... a4 20. Nd4 Rc4 21. Bb2 a3 22. Rac1 Rxc1
23. Bxc1 Nxa2 {White has to be careful already.}) (18... a4 19. Nd4 Rfc8 {
is also possible.}) 19. a4 (19. Bc4 $2 {Ree,H (2480)-Kortschnoj,V (2635) Wijk
aan Zee 1984 (½-½, 56)} Qg6 $1 20. Qg5 (20. f3 Ne3) 20... Nb6 $17 {The
light-squared bishop is in trouble.} 21. Qxg6 hxg6 22. Nd2 Nc2 23. Rb1 Rac8 24.
Bb3 a4 25. Bxc2 Rxc2 26. a3 Nd5 {with crushing domination.}) 19... Nc3 20. Bb2
Nxd3 21. Bxc3 Qg6 22. f3 Rac8 23. Nd4 (23. Rad1 $2 Rxc3 24. Qxc3 Re2 $19) (23.
Bxa5 $6 Rc4 $17 {yields Black a dominating position and the strong threat ...
Nf4.} 24. Bc3 $2 (24. Rad1 $2 Nf4 25. Rde1 Rxe1 26. Rxe1 h6 $19 {The threat is
...Rc2.} 27. Rc1 Rxc1+ 28. Nxc1 Bxf3 $19) 24... Rxc3 $1 (24... Nf4 $2 {runs
into} 25. Rae1 {as the bishop defends the c-file.} Rec8 26. Na5) 25. Qxc3 Re2
26. g3 Qh6 27. h4 Qe3+) 23... Rc4 24. Ra3 h5 25. Ba1 Ne5 {The position remains
balanced since with Black's activity compensates for the inferior pawn
structure.} *

