{[%evp 0,36,17,29,17,-17,-6,-6,10,-20,34,30,51,-2,4,-43,-1,2,18,-4,-10,-19,-26,
-26,14,15,16,17,21,0,0,8,6,8,8,8,34,34,34]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4.
Qc2 {I have used the approved name of this system; even though, as mentioned
before, I consider that 4.e3 corresponds to the "classical" idea better.
Sources are naming this system after either Capablanca, Alekhine, or both!
White's idea is clear: he intends to get the bishop pair with a2-a3 without
being left with double pawns. The main drawback of this system is neglecting
development. We could also add that in some cases the weakness on b3, caused
by the move a2-a3, may be relevant.} b6 $5 {It makes sense to hurry with this
move.} ({The traditional way of reaching a fianchetto is} 4... O-O 5. a3 ({
It is worth mentioning that after} 5. e4 {Black has to react with 5...d5, with
a certain drawish tendency, as if} c5 {as in our lines,} 6. e5 {and the knight
does not have the retreat route ...Ng8-e7 available.}) 5... Bxc3+ 6. Qxc3 b6 (
6... d5 {The dynamic ...d5 seems to be the hottest move nowadays. Black relies
on his home analysis to reach a draw in a somewhat unpleasant position.} 7. Bg5
dxc4 8. Qxc4 b6) 7. Bg5 (7. f3 {is also popular}) 7... Bb7 8. f3 {Black has to
react in the centre to avoid being crushed, but this does not
correspond to the spirit of our repertoire. As we will see, the suggested move
order avoids this variation.}) 5. e4 {An ambitious move, but one that also
offers Black chances for counterplay.} ({If} 5. Nf3 Bb7 {White does not get
much due to refraining from the early a2-a3, which would transpose to some
line examined below.} 6. e3 (6. g3 $6 Nc6 {suddenly creates the unpleasant
threat ...Nxd4.}) (6. Bg5 h6 7. Bh4 g5 8. Bg3 Ne4 {is likely to transpose to
lines discussed later.}) 6... O-O (6... Ne4 {is also good, transposing to a
favourable version of the 4.e3 b6 5.Bd3 Bb7 6.Nf3 Ne4 system, where White
should not play 7.Qc2. However, since we do not have this system in our
repertoire, I have suggested something independent.} 7. Bd3 f5 8. O-O Bxc3 9.
bxc3 O-O) 7. Bd3 (7. Be2 {is more passive.} Ne4 8. O-O Bxc3 9. bxc3 {Since the
knight is not hanging, Black can start playing against the doubled pawns with}
c5 $11) 7... c5 8. a3 (8. O-O {allows the familiar} Bxf3 9. gxf3 cxd4 10. exd4
Nc6 {with good counterplay against White's weaknesses.}) 8... Bxc3+ 9. Qxc3
Bxf3 10. gxf3 Nc6 {with a familiar scenario.}) ({The same as above applies to} 
5. Bg5 Bb7 6. e3 (6. f3 h6 7. Bh4 {runs into} c5 8. dxc5 Bxc5) 6... h6 7. Bh4
g5 8. Bg3 Bxc3+ 9. Qxc3 Ne4 10. Qc2 f5 {with easy play for Black.}) ({The
consistent} 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. Qxc3 Bb7 {is covered in Lines 15 to 22.}) 5... c5 $1
(5... Bb7 $6 {is risky due to} 6. e5 Ne4 (6... Ng8 {may be playable, but not
entirely desirable.}) 7. a3 Bxc3+ 8. bxc3 {and the knight is not stable on e4.}
d6 9. Bd3 f5 10. exf6 Nxf6 11. Ne2 $14 Bxg2 $6 12. Rg1 $16) 6. dxc5 {In this
line, we will examine the variations in which White is heading for the
Hedgehog type of position.} (6. Nf3 cxd4 7. Nxd4 Bb7 {offers Black free
development.} 8. f3 (8. Bd3 Bxc3+ 9. bxc3 {spoils White's structure.} d6 10.
O-O O-O 11. Rd1 Nbd7 12. f3 Qe7 13. a4 Rfc8 $11 {Black cannot dream of more in
the Nimzo-Indian.}) 8... O-O 9. Bg5 h6 10. Bh4 Nc6 11. O-O-O Bxc3 12. Qxc3 (12.
bxc3 Ne5) 12... Nxe4 13. Qe1 Nf6 14. Nb5 d5 {White does not have more than
equalising compensation for the pawn, as his king is not very secure.}) (6. d5
{is examined in Line 13}) ({For} 6. e5 {see Line 14}) (6. a3 {is the subject
of Line 15.}) 6... Bb7 $5 7. Bd3 (7. e5 Ne4 8. cxb6 axb6 {offers Black ample
compensation for the pawn.} 9. Nf3 Qc7 10. Be2 Nxc3 11. bxc3 Bc5 12. Bf4 Nc6
13. O-O Ne7 14. Nd4 Ng6 15. Nb5 Qb8 16. Bg3 Nxe5) 7... bxc5 {The solid
continuation. Black aims at installing a knight on d4.} (7... Bxc5 {leads to
more dynamic play, with the same general evaluation: chances are roughly equal:
} 8. Nf3 Nc6 9. a3 Ng4 10. O-O Qb8 {A typical counter-attacking plan.} 11. Ne2
(11. g3 a5 12. Bf4 d6 $11) 11... Nce5 12. Nxe5 Qxe5 13. Bf4 Qf6 14. b4 (14. Bg3
h5 15. h4 g5 16. hxg5 Qxg5 17. b4 Be7 $17 {Haessel,D (2212)-Ng,G (2228)
Edmonton 2016 (0-1, 50)}) 14... Bxf2+ 15. Rxf2 Qxa1+ 16. Rf1 Qf6 17. h3 Ne5 {
White has lost an exchange and a pawn but can force a draw by repetition.} 18.
Bg3 Qg5 19. Bf4 Qf6 $11) 8. Nge2 (8. Nf3 Nc6 9. O-O {Jelen,I (2427)-Hoelzl,F 
(2398) Bled 2000 (½-½, 49)} d6 10. Rd1 Bxc3 11. Qxc3 e5 $11) 8... d6 9. O-O
Nc6 10. Bg5 h6 11. Bh4 Bxc3 12. Qxc3 g5 13. Bg3 e5 {From statical viewpoint,
Black has an excellent position, but White still has dynamic resources.} 14. f4
$5 exf4 15. Nxf4 gxf4 16. Bh4 {Reminiscent of some Adolf Anderssen games.} Nd4
17. Rxf4 Nh5 $1 18. Bxd8 Nxf4 19. Qd2 Nxd3 {Black has more than enough
material equivalent for the queen, but the forced sequence has not ended yet.}
20. Bf6 Ne5 {[%csl Rd2,Rg1][%cal Ge5f3]} 21. Qa5 Kd7 22. Bxh8 (22. Rd1 $2 Rhe8
$19 {Vigorito,D (2373)-Sevillano,E (2472) Las Vegas 2006 (0-1, 37) Black has a
material advantage and a rock solid position.}) 22... Rxh8 {With three minor
pieces for the queen, Black is not worse.} 23. b4 $2 {does not work due to}
Nec6 24. Qa3 cxb4 25. Qe3 Ne6 $17 {with two wonderful squares for the knights
on e5 and c5.} *

