1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 b6 5. e4 c5 6. e5 {A very direct move
that forces the knight to step back. However, thankfully, we can destroy
White's centre instead of retreating!} cxd4 7. a3 (7. exf6 dxc3 8. bxc3 Qxf6
$17) 7... Bxc3+ 8. bxc3 Ng8 {The knight can easily return into play with ...
Ne7 and the centre are now quite shaky, meaning Black will always have
counterplay.} 9. cxd4 (9. Qe4 {looks active but helps Black develop.} Nc6 10.
cxd4 d5 (10... Bb7 11. Nf3 Nge7 12. Qg4 {offers White some kingside initiative.
}) 11. cxd5 (11. Qg4 Nge7 12. Qxg7 {offers Black strong counterplay in the
centre.} Rg8 13. Qxh7 dxc4 14. Be3 b5) 11... exd5 (11... f5 $5 {also deserves
a mention as the white queen cannot keep both the d4-pawn and the d5-square
under control.} 12. Qf3 {Preventing the blockade with ...Qxd5.} Nxd4 13. Qc3
Qxd5 14. Be3 Nc6 15. Nf3 h6 16. Bc4 Qa5 17. Qxa5 Nxa5 18. Ba2 Ne7 19. Nd4 Kf7 {
with good compensation for the pawn, but Black isn't doing too bad, either.})
12. Qe3 Nge7 13. Nf3 Na5 14. Bd2 Nc4 15. Qf4 O-O 16. Bd3 Nb2 17. Be2 Nc4 {
A typical correspondence chess move.} (17... f6 {is, of course, more natural.})
18. O-O f6 19. Bb4 a5 20. Bxe7 Qxe7 {with unclear play, Canamas Soler, J (2268)
-Ramos Verdu, J (2171) ICCF email 2015 (½-½, 29)}) 9... Bb7 {White has
achieved some rather considerable space advantage, but it is not easy to use
that extra space with the pieces.  The h1-a8 diagonal is a problem for White,
too.} 10. Bb2 (10. Nf3 {allows} Bxf3 11. gxf3 Nc6 12. Bb2 (12. d5 $5 {(Ganguly)
leads to entertaining play:} Nxe5 13. Bb2 Qf6 (13... Nxf3+ $2 14. Ke2 $18) 14.
O-O-O Qf4+ 15. Qd2 Qxd2+ 16. Rxd2 f6 17. f4 Ng6 18. dxe6 dxe6 19. f5 $5 {
White has to use all the dynamic resources in order to avoid being just worse.}
Nf4 $1 {Black has to keep the a2-g8 diagonal defended.} (19... exf5 20. c5 {
followed by Bb5+ offers White more initiative than Black needs to give him,
even though chances are balanced, anyway.}) 20. c5 Ne7 21. fxe6 Nxe6 22. cxb6 (
22. Bc4 Nxc5 $15) (22. Bb5+ Kf7 23. Bc4 Rac8 24. Re1 Rxc5 $19) 22... axb6 23.
Bc4 Rc8 24. Rc2 Kf7 25. Re1 Rc6 {The knight's pin offers White some
compensation for the pawn, but it is hard to see how he could make progress.}
26. Kb1 Rhc8 27. Rec1 {All Black's pieces are immobile with the exception of
the c8-rook. Black can either wait or immediately start rolling his kingside
majority.} g5 28. a4 h5 {White does not have more than a positional draw.})
12... Nge7 13. Rg1 {Baules,J (2358)-Nakamura,H (2763) Batumi 2018 (0-1)} O-O
14. d5 Na5 15. Rd1 (15. Bd3 Ng6) 15... Rc8 16. Qe4 Nb3 17. Bd3 Ng6 18. Bc2 Nc5
19. Qe3 b5 $5 {Black's kingside is solid and he already has counterplay on the
queenside.}) (10. Qd1 $5 {[%cal Gg1f3] is a rather unexpected move, the point
being preparing to finish the kingside development naturally with Nf3. While
the idea isn't exactly poisonless, Black can definitely use the time gained to
generate massive counterplay.} Ne7 11. Nf3 (11. Qg4 Nf5 12. d5 {Cramling
Bellon,A (1959)-Vaishali,R (2329) Stockholm 2018 (0-1, 33)} Qh4 $15) 11... d5 (
11... O-O $6 12. Bd3 {threatening Bxh7+ is unpleasant.}) 12. exd6 Qxd6 13. Be2
O-O 14. O-O Nbc6 15. Bb2 Rfd8 16. Re1 Ng6 17. Rc1 Nce7 18. Bf1 Rac8 {Black has
disposed his forces harmoniously and is ready to meet White's active attempts.
He could think of improving his position with ...Qf4 or ...Nf5.}) ({The
manoeuvre initiated by} 10. Ne2 {wastes a bunch of time while not exactly
improving the horsey, either.} Nc6 11. Bb2 Rc8 12. Ng3 Na5 13. Rc1 Qh4 14. f3
f5 15. Qf2 Ne7 16. Be2 Ba6 $17 {Arnaudov,P (2445)-Volokitin,A (2639) Struga
2014 (0-1, 32)}) 10... Ne7 11. Ne2 Nbc6 12. Ng3 Rc8 {Black has developed his
pieces harmoniously and is already threatening with ...Na5.} 13. Bc3 {
Anticipating ...Na5.} ({The untested} 13. Ne4 $5 $146 {is worth mentioning.}
Nf5 {The only move.} 14. g4 ({White does not have the time for half-measures.} 
14. Rd1 $2 O-O {Planning to undermine the centre with ...Na5 or ...d7-d5, or
to simply add pressure with ...Qh4.} 15. g4 Nh4 16. Nd6 Nxe5 17. Nxb7 Nef3+ 18.
Ke2 Qc7 $19) 14... Ncxd4 (14... d5 {offers White some rather dangerous
initiative.} 15. gxf5 dxe4 16. d5 $1 {The most active way of dealing with the
threat ...Nxd4.} exd5 17. Rg1) 15. Qd3 b5 $3 {Clearing the attacking diagonal
for the queen.} 16. gxf5 Bxe4 17. Qxe4 Qa5+ 18. Kd1 Qa4+ {White should take a
draw by perpetual as stepping out of it in any way loses.} 19. Kd2 $2 Nb3+ 20.
Ke2 (20. Ke3 Nxa1 21. Bxa1 Qxa3+) (20. Ke1 Qa5+ 21. Ke2 Qd2+ 22. Kf3 Qxb2)
20... Rxc4 $19) 13... Na5 $5 $146 {This is the most practical solution. The
following exchange weakens Black's structure but reduces the significance of
White's space advantage.} (13... d5 14. exd6 Qxd6 {may run into} 15. d5 $1 $146
exd5 16. Bxg7 Rg8 17. Qxh7 Ne5 18. Rd1) (13... O-O $5 $146 {is also playable,
though a bit risky.} 14. Bd3 d5 15. exd6 (15. Bxh7+ Kh8 16. h4 dxc4 {
threatening both ...Nxd4 and ...Nd5.}) 15... Qxd6 16. Bxh7+ (16. Rd1 $5 Ng6 17.
O-O Qxa3 18. Ra1 Qd6 {offers White excellent compensation for the pawn but it
is hard to see whether he can threaten Black in any concrete way.}) 16... Kh8
17. Qe4 Qd8 $3 {Anticipating Qh4.} 18. d5 (18. Qh4 Ng6 19. Qxd8 {The queen
does not have enough squares along the h-file due to ...Nf4.} Rfxd8 20. Bxg6
fxg6 21. Rd1 Ne7 22. Bb4 Nf5 23. Nxf5 gxf5 24. c5 Bxg2 {and Black is not worse.
}) 18... f5 19. Qe2 (19. Qxe6 Kxh7 20. dxc6 Rxc6 {hands Black the initiative.}
21. Qe2 Nd5 22. Rd1 Re8 23. Be5 Rce6 $15 24. f4 $2 Nxf4 $1 25. Rxd8 Nxe2 $19)
