1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 b6 5. e4 c5 6. a3 Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 {White
decides to play some sort of a Saemisch attack hybrid. However, the queen may
become vulnerable on c2 and the move ...b7-b6 is useful in this structure as
it prepares all sorts of threats against the c4-pawn.} Bb7 8. Bd3 {The most
natural move, which has a hidden drawback, though.} (8. f3 {doesn't create any
pressure and allows Black to organize his play against White's weaknesses.} Nc6
9. Be3 d6 10. Nh3 Na5 11. Be2 Qc7 12. O-O O-O 13. Bg5 Nd7 14. Rfd1 Rfe8 15. Qa4
Ba6 16. Bf4 Nf8 17. Bg3 Rac8 $17 {Aymard,M (2045)-Kazmin,A ICCF email 2018 
(0-1, 59) The pawn on d4 is doomed in view of the threat ...Qd7.}) (8. e5 {
After White lost a tempo with a2-a3, this pawn advance is less dangerous than
in the line we avoid: 5...Nf6 6.e5.} Ng8 9. Nf3 Ne7 10. Bg5 (10. Bd3 {runs
into the familiar} Bxf3 11. gxf3 Nbc6 {White has structural problems all over
the board and the knights are perfectly suited for exploiting them.} 12. Be3
cxd4 13. cxd4 d6 14. f4 Rc8 15. Qa4 O-O 16. Rd1 d5 $17 {Mohamad,E (2389)-Zhou,
J (2597) Kuala Lumpur 2017 (0-1, 28)}) 10... h6 11. Bh4 cxd4 12. cxd4 (12. Nxd4
Nbc6 {does not offer White enough initiative to compensate for the weaknesses.}
13. Nb5 O-O 14. Nd6 Qc7 15. f4 f6 $15 16. Nxb7 fxe5 $1 $19) 12... Bxf3 13. gxf3
Nbc6 {With the bishop isolated on h4, White has a hard time keeping his
position together.} 14. d5 (14. Qe4 b5 $1 {A familiar idea.} 15. cxb5 Qa5+ 16.
Kd1 Nd5 17. Rc1 Qa4+ 18. Ke1 Nxd4 $19) (14. Rd1 Rc8 $17) 14... exd5 15. cxd5
Nxe5 16. Qe4 Qc7 17. Bxe7 Qc3+ 18. Ke2 Qxa1 19. Bd6 f6 20. f4 Qb2+ 21. Ke3 Qc1+
22. Ke2 Qb2+ 23. Ke3 Qc3+ 24. Ke2 Qc4+ {Galvez Dastin,E (2224)-Quesada Perez,L
(2402) Santa Clara 2017 (0-1, 33)}) (8. d5 {allows Black to develop solidly
and break up the White immobile centre.} d6 9. Bd3 O-O 10. Ne2 Nbd7 11. f4 $2 {
Too optimistic.} (11. Ng3 Re8 12. O-O Ng4 13. h3 Nge5 14. Be2 Qh4 $11) 11... b5
$1 12. cxb5 exd5 13. exd5 Bxd5 14. c4 {Holt,C (2549)-Kollars,D (2586) chess.
com INT 2020 (1-0, 89)} Bxg2 15. Rg1 Bf3 16. Bb2 Re8 17. Bxh7+ Kf8 18. Bd3 d5
19. cxd5 Rc8 20. Rg3 Bh5 $17 {White is poorly coordinated and vulnerable.})
8... b5 $3 {A fantastic dynamic resource, based on the fact that White's only
developed pieces are exposed and standing in each other's way.} (8... d6 {
allows} 9. f4 $14 {with dangerous initiative, as} b5 $6 {does not work due to}
10. cxb5 c4 11. Bxc4 Bxe4 12. Bd3 {and g2 is defended.}) 9. Qb1 {The critical
answer.} (9. cxb5 $2 c4 $15 {wins Black the pawn after the bishop's retreat to
f1} 10. Bxc4 $2 {is just poor} Bxe4 11. Bd3 Bxg2 $19) (9. Rb1 {does not pose
any concrete problems.} bxc4 10. Rxb7 cxd3 11. Qxd3 O-O {White's centre does
not promise him an advantage, as he cannot create a passed pawn.  Moreover, he
is behind in development and the square on c4 is accessible to Black.} 12. Ne2
(12. Bg5 cxd4 13. cxd4 Qa5+ 14. Bd2 Qa4 15. Rb4 Qa6 16. Qxa6 Nxa6 17. Ra4 Nc7
18. f3 d5 19. e5 Nd7 $17 {With a perfect French scenario.}) 12... Qc8 13. Rb1
Qa6 14. Qe3 $2 {White should not have tolerated the queen on a6.} (14. Qxa6
Nxa6 15. f3 cxd4 16. cxd4 d5 $5 17. Bg5 $1 dxe4 18. Bxf6 exf3 19. Bxg7 Kxg7 20.
gxf3 $11) 14... Nc6 15. O-O Rab8 16. Rxb8 Rxb8 17. dxc5 $6 Qc4 18. Nd4 Nxd4 19.
cxd4 Rb3 20. Qd2 Nxe4 $17 {Gongora Reyes,M (2427)-Quesada Perez,Y (2627)
