1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 b6 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. Qxc3 Bb7 7. Nf3 O-O 8.
e3 d6 9. Be2 {As mentioned before, this is the most consistent way of
continuing the development.} Nbd7 10. O-O Ne4 11. Qc2 f5 {This is an important
tabiya. Optically, Black has a pleasant position and certain attacking chances
on the kingside due to such ideas as ...Rf6. However, White has several ways
of trying to make use of his superior space and bishops pair. Two of them are
the possibility of the break d4-d5 and Ne1 followed by f2-f3.} 12. Ne1 {A
straightforward way of neutralizing ...Rf6 which allows Black to start his
attack with a different move order. An important drawback of the last move is
that it ignores the queenside development.} (12. Nd2 {has similar boons and
cons.} Qg5 13. d5 (13. Bf3 Nxd2 14. Bxb7 Nxf1 15. Bxa8 Nxh2 16. Bc6 Nb8 {
wins a pawn.}) (13. f4 Qg6 14. Bf3 Nxd2 15. Bxd2 Bxf3 16. Rxf3 Nf6 17. b4 Ne4
$15 {Tomecek,J-Hajek,M (2315) Czechia 1996 (1-0, 43)}) 13... exd5 14. cxd5 Bxd5
15. Bc4 (15. Nf3 Qg6 16. Qxc7 Nec5 {traps the queen after ...Rfc8.}) 15... Nef6
16. Nf3 Qg4 17. Bxd5+ Nxd5 18. Rd1 {White has some initiative for the missing
pawn.} Qe4 19. Qb3 c6 20. Nd4 Nc5 21. Qa2 Kh8 22. Nxc6 Nc3 23. bxc3 Qxc6 24. c4
{Gurevich,M (2605)-Van der Wiel,J (2495) Hoogeveen 2001 (1-0, 62)} Rae8 25. Bd2
Re6 {with a good regrouping and certain chances on the kingside.}) (12. d5 {
is somewhat premature as nothing would happen over the diagonal.} exd5 13. Nd4
Qf6 14. cxd5 Bxd5 15. f3 Ng5 16. Bd3 {Zhai,M (2324)-Harika,D (2508) China 2015
(0-1, 70)} Ne5 17. Bxf5 Ngxf3+ 18. gxf3 c5 19. Bxh7+ Kh8 $15) (12. b4 {is
covered in Lines 20 and 21.}) 12... Qh4 $1 {Preparing to retreat to g5 with
the knight without obstructing the queen.} 13. f3 (13. g3 Ng5 14. f3 Nh3+ 15.
Kh1 Qh6 16. Ng2 g5 {offers Black a consisetnt attacking plan.}) 13... Ng5 {
Black is already threatening with ...Rf6-h6, so White HAS to take immediate
action.} 14. c5 {The critical move, aiming at proving that Black's committal
attacking moves have weakened the defence in the other board sectors.} (14. Nd3
Rf6 15. g3 Nh3+ (15... Qh5 16. Nf4 Nh3+ 17. Nxh3 Qxh3 18. e4 fxe4 19. fxe4
Rxf1+ 20. Bxf1 Qh5 21. Bg2 Rf8 22. Be3 Nf6 $11 {Murzin,L (2195)-Akobian,V 
(2575) Las Vegas 2006 (0-1, 29)}) 16. Kg2 Qh5 17. Nf4 Nxf4+ 18. exf4 {
Kukhmazov,A (2395)-Alekseev,E (2620) St Petersburg 2018 (0-1, 31)} c5 19. dxc5
(19. Be3 cxd4 20. Bxd4 e5 $17) 19... bxc5 $15 {[%cal Ge6e5] followed by ...
e6-e5.}) (14. Bd1 Rf6 15. Qf2 Qh5 16. Nd3 e5 17. d5 {Hort,V (2570)-Polugaevsky,
L (2595) Biel 1989 (½-½, 18)} Rh6 18. Qg3 c6 {Trying to add the bishop to
the attack.} 19. f4 $6 Ne4 $1 $15) (14. d5 e5 $146) 14... dxc5 15. dxc5 bxc5
16. b4 (16. Bb5 Rad8 17. Qf2 Qh5 18. Nd3 Nb6 {with unclear play as if} 19. Nxc5
$2 Bxf3 $17) 16... Rf6 {Black has to keep throwing more wood into the fire.}
17. Bb5 (17. g3 Nh3+ 18. Kh1 Qh5 19. bxc5 Bc6 $1 {This lovely blockading move
makes the queenside perfectly safe.} 20. Rb1 Ng5 21. Bb5 Ne5 22. Bxc6 Nxc6 23.
Rf2 e5 {With excellent play, Peterc,C (2298)-De la Pena Balbuena,I (2327) ICCF
email 2013 (½-½, 28)}) 17... Rh6 18. g3 (18. Bxd7 $2 Qxh2+ 19. Kf2 Rd8 20.
Bb5 Bxf3 $5 21. Nxf3 Nh3+ 22. Ke1 Qg3+ 23. Rf2 Nxf2 24. Qxf2 Rh1+ 25. Ke2 Qd6
$19) (18. h3 Qg3 $19) 18... Nh3+ 19. Kh1 Qe7 {Black has managed to weaken the
enemy kingside, now he has to make sure the pieces don't suddenly start
lacking coordination.} 20. e4 (20. Bxd7 Qxd7 21. Qxc5 Qd1 $19) (20. bxc5 Nxc5
21. e4 Rh5 22. exf5 Rxf5 {[%cal Ga8f8,Gh3g5] followed by ...Raf8 and ...Ng5.})
20... Rh5 21. exf5 Ne5 $1 {Preparing ...Rxf5 under the best possible
circumstances.} (21... Rxf5 $6 {ran into} 22. Bd3 Raf8 (22... Rh5 23. g4 $1)
23. Bxf5 Rxf5 24. Kg2 Ng5 25. Bxg5 Qxg5 26. Rd1 Ne5 27. Qd2 {with insufficient
