1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 b6 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. Qxc3 Bb7 7. Nf3 O-O 8.
g3 {This seemingly unambitious move is aimed at restricting Black's
counterplay.  White hopes that his space advantage and bishop pair will ensure
him the better chances in a slow middlegame.  Specifically, White is reducing
Black's attacking chances on the kingside while also not letting the b7-bishop
get too active. It is also correct that his king's bishop isn't going to be
too active, it's likely the light-squared bishops will get traded at some
point.} d6 9. Bg2 Nbd7 {The position is very similar to that examined in Line
9 in another database of mine on Bogo-Indian.} 10. O-O (10. b4 {offers Black a
clear plan on generating queenside counterplay:} a5 11. Bb2 (11. b5 Rc8 12. O-O
c6 $5 13. bxc6 Bxc6 14. Bf4 Qe7 {Now, the c4-pawn is likely to be a liability.}
) 11... axb4 12. axb4 Rxa1+ 13. Bxa1 b5 $1 {Those familiar with my Bogoindian
database will remember this way of fighting for the light squares.} 14. cxb5 {
Buss, R (2361)-Moor, O (2323) Switzerland 2016 (1-0, 83)} Nb6 $11 {White's extra
pawn is not relevant, while our minor pieces are amazing.}) 10... a5 {Planning
to block the queenside with ...a5-a4.} ({The plan we use after 8.e3 no longer
works equally well.} 10... Ne4 11. Qc2 Rb8 {Defending the bishop in order to
remove the knight's pin, but wasting a tempo.} (11... f5 12. Ng5 $1 {This is
the point, the pin along the long diagonal is unpleasant.}) 12. Nh4 {Black is
likely to lose ground in the centre.}) 11. b3 (11. b4 {once again helps Black.}
axb4 12. axb4 Rxa1 13. Qxa1 b5 $1 $146 14. cxb5 Bd5 15. Bg5 Qb8 16. Bxf6 Nxf6
17. Qa5 Bc4 $11) 11... Qb8 {I've recommended the same plan in the
aforementioned database on the Bogo-Indian.  Black is preparing ...b6-b5. 
Compared to Bogo, the queen isn't on d2 and the bishop isn't on b2, but these
differences are rather insignificant.} ({Hurrying with the plan allows White
to react accordingly:} 11... a4 12. b4 b5 $6 13. cxb5 Qb8 14. Bb2 Rc8 15. Rfc1 (
15. Rac1 {is too slow:} Bd5 16. Nd2 Bxg2 17. Kxg2 Qxb5 {Rios,C (2461)-Adams,M 
(2701) chess.com INT 2020 (0-1, 39)}) 15... Be4 (15... Bd5 16. Bf1) 16. Bf1
Qxb5 17. Nd2 {Black will soon lose ground on the queenside and in the centre.})
(11... Qe7 {is natural, but fails to put pressure on White.} 12. Bb2 Rfe8 13.
Rfe1 Be4 14. Rad1 h6 15. Bf1 c6 16. Nd2 Bh7 17. e4 e5 18. Bg2 $14 {Maiorov,N 
(2522)-Malek,D (2376) Hofheim 2014 (1-0, 34)}) 12. Bb2 {This could be a
meeting point between the two similar variations if White played 12.Qd2-c3 in
the Bogo-Indian. White clearly has more useful moves in the Bogo, so this
position is a bit more comfortable for us than that one.} (12. Re1 $5 {was
played by Carlsen and happens to be an interesting attempt of stopping Black's
idea.} c5 $5 $146 {Since White's development is slow, now it is a good moment
to switch plans.} (12... Re8 13. Bb2 Be4 14. Bf1 e5 15. Nd2 exd4 16. Qxd4 Bc6
17. e4 $14 {Carlsen,M (2823)-Ivanchuk,V (2765) Sao Paulo/Bilbao 2011 (½-½,
79)}) (12... Be4 13. Bf1 b5 {runs into} 14. cxb5 Qxb5 15. Nd2 $14 {for instance
} Bb7 16. e4 {and Black does not have enough space for his pieces, for instance
} Qh5 $2 17. Qxc7 $18) 13. Bb2 ({In the line below, lack of pressure along the
d-file offers Black certain freedom of choice. Therefore,} 13. Rd1 {deserves
mentioning. However, this obviously wastes time.} Be4 14. Bb2 a4 $5 15. b4 cxb4
16. Qxb4 {not giving Black the plan based on ...b6-b5.} d5 $11 {with active
play and good control on light squares.}) 13... cxd4 14. Qxd4 (14. Nxd4 {
makes things simpler for Black.} Bxg2 15. Kxg2 a4 $5 {a clear way to the
immediate equality.} 16. b4 Rc8 17. Nb5 Ne5 18. Nxd6 Qxd6 19. Qxe5 Qxe5 20.
Bxe5 Rxc4 21. Rad1 Nd5 22. e4 Nc3 23. Rd6 Nb5 24. Rxb6 Nxa3 $11) 14... e5 {
The main point is that with the passive e1-rook White was not in time to set
up pressure on d6.} 15. Qc3 (15. Qe3 Nc5 {will now force White to waste more
time as ...Ng4 is underway.} 16. Rac1 $2 Ng4 17. Qg5 Nxf2 $1 $19) 15... Nc5 16.
Rad1 Re8 17. Bh3 Qc7 18. Nh4 Rad8 $11 {Black has achieved a solid structure
and a natural regrouping.} 19. Nf5 $6 Bc8 20. Qe3 h6 $1 21. f3 Be6 {Suddenly,
White is unstable on both flanks. ...b6-b5 and ...a5-a4 is coming}) ({A
natural question is what happens if White plays} 12. Rd1 {at once, as in the
line above the rook was needed on the d-file.} Be4 13. Bf1 b5 $1 {This is
possible due to small detail.} 14. cxb5 Qxb5 15. Nd2 (15. Qxc7 {endangers
the queen and offers Black more than one way of over the c-file. The strongest
answer is} a4 $17 {threatening to trap the queen with ...Nd5 and ...Ra6,
without allowing the intermediate a3-a4. And if} 16. bxa4 Qxa4 {attacking the
ambitious rook.} 17. Bf4 Nd5 18. Qc1 Rfc8 19. Qd2 Rc2 20. Qe1 Nxf4 21. gxf4
Bxf3 22. exf3 Nf6 $15) 15... Bb7 16. e4 Qh5 $1 {This is the point! Black gains
a tempo by attacking the rook.} 17. Re1 c5 18. Bb2 Rfc8 $11 {with harmonious
play for Black.}) 12... Be4 13. Bh3 {Preparing to tuck the enemy bishop away.}
(13. a4 {stabilizes the queenside while also weakening b4} Qe8 $146 14. Rad1
Rd8 15. Rfe1 h6 {Preparing the bishop's retreat to h7.} (15... Qe7 16. Bh3 Bb7
17. d5 e5 18. Nh4 $14) 16. Bf1 Bh7 17. Nd2 e5 {White's coordination is now
rather ugly, so it's easy for us to generate counterplay in the centre.} 18. f3
(18. e4 exd4 19. Qxd4 Qe5 $11) (18. d5 Nc5 19. Bg2 Nfd7 $15 {followed by ...
f7-f5.}) 18... exd4 19. Qxd4 Qe5 20. e4 Qxd4+ 21. Bxd4 Nc5 $11 {Black's
queenside stability is a direct consequence of a3-a4. Next, he could transfer
the other knight to c6 or b4 and then think of breaking with ...f7-f5. If
g3-g4, he could simply re-route the bishop to the a2-g8 diagonal and think of
a kingside blockade.}) (13. Nd2 Bxg2 14. Kxg2 {frees Black's play.} Qb7+ 15.
Qf3 (15. f3 d5 $11) (15. Kg1 d5 $11) 15... Qxf3+ $1 $146 16. exf3 (16. Kxf3
Rfe8 17. Kg2 e5 $11) (16. Nxf3 Ne4 17. Rfd1 f5 18. Ne1 Kf7 $11) 16... d5 17. a4
Rfd8 18. Rac1 (18. Rfd1 Nb8 19. Rac1 Na6 $11) 18... dxc4 19. bxc4 Nc5 $1 {
with sudden counterplay.}) 13... b5 $1 (13... a4 $6 14. b4 b5 {runs into} 15.
d5 $1 {Therefore, it is better to leave the c5-square available for the knight.
}) 14. Nd2 (14. cxb5 Qxb5 15. Qxc7 Qxe2 16. Ng5 Bd5 $19) (14. d5 e5 15. Nd2 Nc5
$1) 14... bxc4 15. bxc4 Nb6 {Black has achieved certain queenside counterplay.
White is undeveloped, his c4 and a4-pawns are vulnerable.} 16. Qc1 $5 $146 (16.
a4 Bc6 17. Bg2 Bxg2 18. Kxg2 Qe8 19. Qb3 Qc6+ 20. Qf3 (20. f3 Rab8 21. Rfb1 d5)
20... Qd7 21. Qb3 $11) (16. Nxe4 {hands Black the initiative.} Nxe4 17. Qc2
Nxc4 $1 18. Qxc4 (18. Qxe4 d5 19. Qc2 Qxb2 $17) 18... Qxb2 19. Rfb1 (19. Qxc7
Rfc8 20. Qe7 d5 {offers Black active play.}) (19. Rfc1 d5 20. Qd3 c5 21. dxc5
Nxc5 22. Qc3 Qxc3 23. Rxc3 Ne4 $17 {Hilverda,A (2329)-Wirig,A (2481) Metz 2013
(0-1, 36)}) 19... Nd2 20. Rxb2 Nxc4 21. Rc2 d5 22. Bf1 c5 {The simplest if
Black is content with a draw.} (22... Nd6 $5 23. Rxc7 $6 Nb5) 23. dxc5 Rfc8 $11
) 16... d5 17. Nxe4 (17. f3 Bf5 18. g4 (18. Bg2 Na4 19. Ra2 Nxb2 20. Rxb2 Qa7
21. c5 Rab8 $11) 18... Bg6 19. a4 dxc4 20. e4 Rc8 21. Ba3 c5 22. Bxc5 Nfd7 23.
f4 Nxc5 24. dxc5 Rxc5 25. f5 c3 26. fxg6 hxg6 {with active play for the piece.}
) 17... Nxe4 18. cxd5 exd5 19. Bg2 (19. Qc6 Nc4 20. Qxd5 (20. Bc1 Nc3 21. Re1
Qb6 22. Qxb6 cxb6 $15) 20... Qxb2 21. Qxc4 Nd2 22. Qc1 Qxc1 23. Rfxc1 Nb3 $15)
19... f5 20. Qc6 Rf6 21. Qc2 Nc4 {Black's activity more than compensates for
his imperfect structure.} *

